  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What should be my daily schedule?",
  "response": "Creating a daily schedule depends on your personal goals, responsibilities, and preferences. However, I can provide a general framework that you can customize to fit your needs.\n\n### Sample Daily Schedule\n\n#### Morning\n- **6:30 AM - 7:00 AM**: Wake up and morning routine (brush teeth, wash face, etc.)\n- **7:00 AM - 7:30 AM**: Exercise (yoga, jogging, gym, etc.)\n- **7:30 AM - 8:00 AM**: Breakfast\n- **8:00 AM - 8:15 AM**: Plan your day (review tasks, set goals)\n\n#### Work/School\n- **8:15 AM - 12:00 PM**: Focused work/study session (prioritize tasks)\n    - Break every 1 hour for 5-10 minutes\n- **12:00 PM - 1:00 PM**: Lunch break (take a walk or relax)\n\n#### Afternoon\n- **1:00 PM - 3:30 PM**: Continue work/study\n    - Break every 1 hour for 5-10 minutes\n- **3:30 PM - 4:00 PM**: Short break (snack, stretch)\n\n#### Late Afternoon\n- **4:00 PM - 6:00 PM**: Finish work/studies, wrap up tasks\n- **6:00 PM - 7:00 PM**: Dinner and downtime (read, watch TV, etc.)\n\n#### Evening\n- **7:00 PM - 8:00 PM**: Learn a new skill (online course, hobby)\n- **8:00 PM - 9:00 PM**: Family time or socializing (phone calls, visits)\n- **9:00 PM - 10:00 PM**: Wind down (meditation, reading, etc.)\n- **10:00 PM**: Prepare for bed (limit screen time, relax)\n\n### Tips:\n- Adjust the times to fit your own wake-up and sleep needs.\n- Prioritize important tasks first when you\u2019re most alert.\n- Include breaks to maintain productivity and mental clarity.\n- Stay flexible; life can be unpredictable!\n\nFeel free to modify this template based on your specific commitments, whether that\u2019s work, study, family responsibilities, or personal interests.",
